    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-08-16T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-08-16T23:00:00-05:00" n="183"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d183">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.84/15315: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hong Kong</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Southard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hong Kong</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-08-17T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 17, 1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 7:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>262. Continuing my No. 260, August 16, 3 p.m.<note n="82" xml:id="d183fn82">Not
                        printed.</note> Qualified observers here report that Japanese occupation of
                    towns and places on the Hong Kong–Kwangtung frontier from the Pearl River to
                    Mirs Bay is apparently being with a view to some permanence and closing of
                    frontier to all traffic (which in recent months has reached almost normal
                    volume) between this colony and the hinterland. Observers report about 2,000
                    Japanese troops strung along frontier. Chinese resistance reported negligible
                    and there have been comparatively few refugees so far. Government here was
                    previously informed by Japanese of their intention to police frontier and no
                    incidents are anticipated although British soldiers and police have been
                    stationed all along this side of the frontier.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking, Canton, Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Southard</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
